I have been investigating another approach using two more columns on the sample table and a trigger for referential integrity.
This means that a sample can only have one provenance, which is as it should be.

The two columns are:
ProvenanceTable
ProvenanceID

The provenance table contains the name of the provenance joining table to be used and the provenance id contains the id within that joining table.
I have written the trigger function and it all looks do-able.

```
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION checkprovintegrity()
  RETURNS trigger AS
$BODY$
DECLARE
    TableName varchar;
    ProvIdentifier int;
    Plantid int;

    TableNameCount int;
    IdentifierCount int;

BEGIN
    TableName := NEW."ProvenanceTable";
    ProvIdentifier := NEW."ProvenanceID";
    Plantid := NEW."Plant_id";

    -- if the plant is set then we don't need to check the provenance
    if Plantid IS NOT Null THEN
        RETURN NEW;
    END IF;

    select count(*) into TableNameCount
        from dynamic_models_dynamicmodel 
        where db_table = TableName;

    if TableNameCount = 0 THEN
        RAISE EXCEPTION 'Nonexistent Table --> %', TableName USING HINT = 'Please check provenance table name';
    END IF;


    EXECUTE 'SELECT count(*) FROM '||TableName ||' WHERE id = '|| ProvIdentifier
       INTO IdentifierCount
       USING TableName,ProvIdentifier;

    if IdentifierCount = 0 THEN
        RAISE EXCEPTION 'Nonexistent Provenance --> % in Table --> %', ProvIdentifier, TableName 
            USING HINT = 'Please check provenance table name and/or provenance identifier';
    END IF;

    return NEW;
END;
$BODY$
  LANGUAGE plpgsql VOLATILE
  COST 100;
ALTER FUNCTION checkprovintegrity()
  OWNER TO keaadmin;

```

